  "chunk_index": 14,
  "summary": "Mrs. Rymes discusses her husband, an engineer who traveled to Sweden in early August, with Detective Hakast and Colin Lamb. She mentions his interest in electric trains, which run through their hallway. Following the conversation, Hakast asks the children, Bill and Ted, to show them the garden at 62 Wilbraham Crescent. The garden contains various plants and scientific models, and from the space between an apple and a pear tree, the rear of Miss Pemshaw’s house at number 19—the murder site—is visible.\n\nThe children explain that they did not see or hear anything during the murder because they were watching a movie. They note that although Miss Pemshaw is blind, she moves easily through her garden. Colin discovers a hosepipe near the pear tree and realizes the children have used it to spray things. Bill and Ted reveal they can access Miss Pemshaw's garden by passing through a hole in the barbed wire fence that connects to Mrs. Hamm's garden.\n\nHakast suggests the children may have found clues while exploring. Bill and Ted present a collection of items found in a knotted handkerchief, including a cup handle, a pottery shard, a broken sponge, a rusty fork, a coin, a clothespin, a piece of colored glass, and half a pair of scissors. Hakast takes the glass, while Colin examines a non-British coin. As they walk, Colin speculates that Mr. Rymes's frequent travels might serve as a cover for something else. Hakast then suggests visiting the MacNorton house, where retired professors live, noting its garden also connects to number 19. Upon arriving, they are met by a young woman who reacts with fear when Hakast identifies himself as police.",
